content='The error message:

Unexpected error: 'str' object has no attribute 'isoformat'

means that somewhere in your code, you are calling .isoformat() on a string object, but .isoformat() is a method for datetime objects, not strings.

This usually happens when you expect a variable to be a datetime object, but it is actually a string. For example:

```python
date_str = "2024-06-01"
print(date_str.isoformat())  # This will raise the error
```

To fix this, you need to ensure that the variable is a datetime object before calling .isoformat(). For example:

```python
from datetime import datetime

date_str = "2024-06-01"
date_obj = datetime.fromisoformat(date_str)
print(date_obj.isoformat())  # This will work
```

If you show me the relevant part of your code, I can help you pinpoint and fix the exact issue!' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={}
